26 SECTION 5.(a) G.S. 35A-1230 reads as rewritten:
27 "§ 35A-1230. Bond required before receiving property.
28 Except as otherwise provided by G.S. 35A-1212.1 and G.S. 35A-1225(a), no general
29 guardian or guardian of the estate shall be permitted to receive the ward's property until he has
30 given sufficient surety, approved by the clerk, to account for and apply the same under the
31 direction of the court, provided that if the guardian is a nonresident of this State and the value of
32 the property received exceeds one thousand dollars ($1,000) the surety shall be a bond under
33 G.S. 35A-1231(a) executed by a duly authorized surety company, or secured by cash in an
34 amount equal to the amount of the bond or by a mortgage executed under Chapter 109 of the
35 General Statutes on real estate located in the county, the value of which, excluding all prior liens
36 and encumbrances, shall be at least one and one-fourth times the amount of the bond; and further
37 provided that the nonresident shall appoint a resident agent to accept service of process in all
38 actions and proceedings with respect to the guardianship. The clerk shall not require a guardian
39 of the person who is a resident of North Carolina to post a bond; the clerk may require a
40 nonresident guardian of the person to post a bond or other security for the faithful performance
41 of the guardian's duties. As provided in G.S. 53-159 and G.S. 53-366(a)(10), no bond is required
42 of a bank or trust company licensed to do business in this State that has powers or privileges
43 granted in the charter to serve as guardian."
