4 MODIFY PROVISIONS REGARDING THE SUSPENSION, REMOVAL, OR
5 REINSTATEMENT OF CLERKS
6 SECTION 13.(a) G.S. 7A-105 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 7A-105. Suspension, removal, and reinstatement of clerk.
8 (a) A clerk of superior court may be suspended or removed from office for willful
9 misconduct or mental or physical incapacity and reinstated, under the same procedures as are
10 applicable to a superior court district attorney, except that the procedure shall be initiated by the
11 filing of a sworn affidavit with the chief district judge of the district in which the clerk resides,
12 and the hearing shall be conducted by the senior regular resident superior court judge serving the
13 county of the clerk's residence. If suspension is ordered, the judge shall appoint some qualified
14 person to act as clerk during the period of the suspension.incapacity.
15 (b) A proceeding to suspend or remove a clerk of superior court shall be commenced in
16 the superior court division and county in which the clerk resides by filing in paper with the chief
17 district court judge (i) a sworn affidavit charging one or more grounds for removal of the clerk
18 of superior court and (ii) a certificate of service showing service on the respondent clerk in
19 accordance with Rule 5(b1) of the Rules of Civil Procedure. Service of the sworn affidavit must
20 be made in a manner provided under Rule 5(b) of the Rules of Civil Procedure. The sworn
21 affidavits are subject to the requirements of Rule 11 of the Rules of Civil Procedure, including
22 imposition of sanctions as appropriate by the court. The clerk shall collect superior court costs
23 set forth in G.S. 7A-305, unless the proceeding is filed by an elected or appointed official of the
24 North Carolina Judicial Branch, in which case costs shall be waived. No summons shall be issued.
25 If the required court costs are not paid within 30 days of the proceeding being commenced, the
26 chief district court judge shall forward the matter to the senior resident superior court judge who
27 shall dismiss the proceeding without prejudice.
28 (c) Upon commencement of the proceeding and confirmation of the payment of the costs
29 required under subsection (b) of this section, the chief district court judge shall immediately
30 provide notice of the filing to the senior regular resident superior court judge for the district or
31 set of districts as defined in G.S. 7A-41.1(a) in which the respondent clerk's county of residence
32 is located. Within 10 days of receiving notice, the senior regular resident superior court judge
33 shall review the sworn affidavit and determine, without a hearing, whether the charges, if true,
34 constitute grounds for removal and whether there is probable cause for believing that the charges
35 are true. If the judge finds either that the charges, if true, do not constitute grounds for removal
36 or that no probable cause exists for believing that the charges are true, the judge shall dismiss the
37 proceeding. Otherwise, the judge shall enter a written order, findings of fact, and conclusions of
38 law detailing which charges would constitute grounds for removal and the probable cause for
39 believing that those charges are true. If the judge finds facts based on the sworn affidavit that
40 immediate and irreparable injury, loss, or damage will result to the public or the administration
41 of justice if the clerk remains in office until a final determination of the charges on the merits,
42 the judge also may enter an order suspending the clerk of superior court from performing the
43 duties of the office until a final determination of the charges on the merits. The salary of the clerk
44 of superior court continues during any such suspension. The court shall serve any order of
45 dismissal, order establishing probable cause, or order of suspension on the parties under Rule 5
46 of the Rules of Civil Procedure as soon as practicable after entry of the order.
47 (d) If the proceeding is not dismissed, the senior regular resident superior court judge
48 shall set a hearing upon the charges found to be supported by probable cause under subsection
49 (c) of this section for not less than 30 days nor more than 60 days after service of the order
50 establishing probable cause on the clerk, unless continued for good cause shown. In the hearing,
51 the court shall hear evidence and make findings of fact and conclusions of law resolving the
Page 14 House Bill 620-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 charges based on clear and convincing evidence. The hearing shall be recorded and open to the
2 public. If the court concludes that grounds for removal exist, the superior court judge shall enter
3 a written order, findings of fact, and conclusions of law permanently removing the clerk of
4 superior court from office and terminating the clerk's salary. If the court finds that no grounds
5 for removal exist, any pending suspension of the clerk shall end immediately and the court shall
6 enter an order of dismissal.
7 The North Carolina Rules of Evidence shall apply to proceedings commenced under this
8 section. The following North Carolina Rules of Civil Procedure shall apply to proceedings
9 commenced under this section to the extent the Rules do not conflict with this section: Rule 5,
10 Rule 11, Rule 45, Rule 46, Rule 52. The parties may issue process under Rule 45 to compel the
11 attendance of witnesses at the hearing and to compel the production of evidence both prior to and
12 at the hearing. Parties must exchange all evidence that they intend to offer at the hearing on the
13 merits at least five days prior to the hearing along with a list of all witnesses that they intend to
14 call.
15 (e) The clerk of superior court may appeal from an order of removal to the Court of
16 Appeals on the basis of error of law by the presiding judge. Pending decision of the case on
17 appeal, the clerk of superior court shall not perform any of the duties of the office. If, upon final
18 determination, the clerk of superior court is ordered reinstated either by the appellate division or
19 by the superior court upon remand, the clerk's salary shall be restored from the date of the original
20 order of removal.
21 (f) If the clerk is prohibited from performing the duties of the office under this section
22 prior to final resolution due either to an order of suspension or to an appeal of an order of removal,
23 the judge shall appoint some qualified person to act as clerk until final resolution.
24 (g) The sworn affidavit and other filings related to the proceeding are confidential unless
25 the senior regular resident superior court judge enters a written order establishing probable cause
26 as described in subsection (c) of this section. The parties to the proceeding may obtain copies of
27 the sworn affidavit and other filings related to the proceeding at any time.
28 (h) If criminal charges are filed against the clerk that relate to factual allegations in a
29 pending sworn affidavit for removal and a judge entered a probable cause order pursuant to
30 subsection (c) of this section, the presiding judge may stay the removal proceeding until the
31 criminal case is resolved. A stay may be granted at any time in the proceeding following the
32 probable cause determination."
33 SECTION 13.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law and applies to
34 proceedings based upon clerk conduct occurring on or after that date.
