33 GRANT NORTH CAROLINA STATE BAR AUTHORITY TO DISCIPLINE
34 OUT-OF-STATE ATTORNEYS PRACTICING IN NORTH CAROLINA
35 SECTION 20. G.S. 84-28 reads as rewritten:
36 "§ 84-28. Discipline and disbarment.
37 (a) Any attorney admitted to practice law in this State State, any attorney admitted for
38 limited practice under G.S. 84-4.1, or any attorney not admitted to practice law in this State who
39 renders or offers to render any legal services in this State is subject to the disciplinary jurisdiction
40 of the Council under such rules and procedures as the Council shall adopt as provided in
41 G.S. 84-23.
42 …
43 (b) The following acts or omissions by a member of the North Carolina State Bar or any
44 attorney admitted for limited practice under G.S. 84-4.1, any attorney subject to the disciplinary
45 jurisdiction of the Council as provided in subsection (a) of this section, individually or in concert
46 with any other person or persons, shall constitute misconduct and shall be grounds for discipline
47 whether the act or omission occurred in the course of an attorney-client relationship or otherwise:
48 (1) Conviction of, or a tender and acceptance of a plea of guilty or no contest to,
49 a criminal offense showing professional unfitness;
50 (2) The violation of the Rules of Professional Conduct adopted and promulgated
51 by the Council in effect at the time of the act;
House Bill 620-Second Edition Page 21

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Knowing misrepresentation of any facts or circumstances surrounding any
2 complaint, allegation or charge of misconduct; failure to answer any formal
3 inquiry or complaint issued by or in the name of the North Carolina State Bar
4 in any disciplinary matter; or contempt of the Council or any committee of the
5 North Carolina State Bar.
6 …
7 (d) Any attorney admitted to practice law in this State, subject to the disciplinary
8 jurisdiction of the Council as provided in subsection (a) of this section who is convicted of or has
9 tendered and has had accepted, a plea of guilty or no contest to, a criminal offense showing
10 professional unfitness, may be disciplined based upon the conviction, without awaiting the
11 outcome of any appeals of the conviction. An order of discipline based solely upon a conviction
12 of a criminal offense showing professional unfitness shall be vacated immediately upon receipt
13 by the Secretary of the North Carolina State Bar of a certified copy of a judgment or order
14 reversing the conviction. The fact that the attorney's criminal conviction has been overturned on
15 appeal shall not prevent the North Carolina State Bar from conducting a disciplinary proceeding
16 against the attorney based upon the same underlying facts or events that were the subject of the
17 criminal proceeding.
18 …
19 (e) Any attorney admitted to practice law in this State subject to the disciplinary
20 jurisdiction of the Council as provided in subsection (a) of this section who is disciplined in
21 another jurisdiction shall be subject to the same discipline in this State: Provided, that the
22 discipline imposed in the other jurisdiction does not exceed that provided for in subsection (c)
23 above of this section and that the attorney was not deprived of due process in the other
24 jurisdiction.
25 (f) Upon application by the North Carolina State Bar, misconduct by an attorney
26 admitted to practice in this State subject to the disciplinary jurisdiction of the Council as provided
27 in subsection (a) of this section may be restrained or enjoined where the necessity for prompt
28 action exists regardless of whether a disciplinary proceeding in the matter of the conduct is
29 pending. The application shall be filed in the Superior Court of Wake County and shall be
30 governed by the procedure set forth in G.S. 1A-1, Rule 65."
31
32 SUBMISSION OF PHYSICAL DOCUMENTS TO CLERK
33 SECTION 21. G.S. 7A-49.5 reads as rewritten:
34 "§ 7A-49.5. Statewide electronic filing in courts.
35 (a) The General Assembly finds that the electronic filing of pleadings and other
36 documents required to be filed with the courts may be a more economical, efficient, and
37 satisfactory procedure to handle the volumes of paperwork routinely filed with, handled by, and
38 disseminated by the courts of this State, and therefore authorizes the use of electronic filing in
39 the courts of this State.
40 (b) The Supreme Court may adopt rules governing this process and associated costs and
41 may supervise its implementation and operation through the Administrative Office of the Courts.
42 The rules adopted under this section shall address the waiver of electronic fees for indigents.
43 (b1) The Supreme Court shall promulgate rules authorizing electronic filing and electronic
44 signatures in the General Court of Justice. The rules shall require registration to participate in
45 electronic filing and provide security procedures that include a mandatory submission of a form
46 of identification to electronically file pro se.
47 (b2) A physical document that has been verified, notarized, acknowledged, sworn to,
48 certified, exemplified, contains a seal, or made under oath may be converted to an electronic
49 format for filing with the General Court of Justice. The electronic version of the document that
50 is filed with and maintained within the electronic filing and case management systems shall
51 constitute the official version of the court record. Notwithstanding the provisions of this
Page 22 House Bill 620-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 subsection, original wills and codicils must also be physically submitted to the clerk and held by
2 the clerk of superior court pursuant to G.S. 28A-2A-13.
3 (c) The Administrative Office of the Courts may contract with a vendor to provide
4 electronic filing in the courts.
5 (d) Any funds received by the Administrative Office of the Courts from the vendor
6 selected pursuant to subsection (c) of this section, other than applicable statutory court costs, as
7 a result of electronic filing, shall be deposited in the Court Information Technology Fund in
8 accordance with G.S. 7A-343.2.
9 (e) The Supreme Court may require that in all cases in which the seal of any court or
10 judicial office is required by law to be affixed to any paper issuing from a court or office, the
11 word "seal" shall be construed to include an impression of the official seal, made upon the paper
12 alone, an impression made by means of a wafer or of wax affixed thereto, or an electronic image
13 adopted as the official seal affixed thereto."
14
15 SEVERABILITY CLAUSE AND EFFECTIVE DATE
16 SECTION 22.(a) If any section or provision of this act is declared unconstitutional
17 or invalid by the courts, it does not affect the validity of this act as a whole or any portion other
18 than the portion declared to be unconstitutional or invalid.
19 SECTION 22.(b) Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
20 law.
